    {
        "client_msg_id": "e68a90e9-3ab3-4e4b-ab71-0918bd50de36",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "What I've found as a hiring manager is that there is an unconscious bias to extend offers to writers who interview well. And if the job is really about writing 8 hours a day, the most important aspect is the writing. So, we usually did a 1 hour writing assignment as part of the interview process to really hone in on writing skills. Also, comparing writing samples across candidates is very difficult due to subject matter, length, etc. I liked having something to compare candidates against each other that had the same prompt. It was usually a few different types of writing, and there wasn't a way for the person to completely finish in the time allotted, so it also gave the hiring team insight into the candidate's writing process, and usually showed how detail oriented the person is. I've also been in a situation where we have asked candidates to write entire blogs as part of the interview process since that task most mirrored what the person would be doing day in and day out. Anything that required outside time and work we compensated as we would a freelancer.",
        "user": "U02GGFE8GDP",
        "ts": "1633009676.037300",
